nks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hubert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."],"variants":[{"name":"Hupprecht","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Huppert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]},{"name":"Hugbert","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>hug</i> ‘heart, mind, spirit’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was popular among the Normans, who introduced it to Britain, where it was later reinforced by settlers from the Low Countries. An 8th-century  St Hubert  succeeded  St Lambert  as bishop of Maastricht and is regarded as the patron of hunters, since, like  St Eustace , he is supposed to have seen a vision of Christ crucified between the antlers of a stag."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Hubert de Munchensy was born in 1065, in Normandy, France as the son of Baron Hubert de Munchensy. He had at least 4 sons and 1 daughter with Muriel de Valoignes. He died about 1116, in Old Abingdon Abbey, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1065–Abt 1116":"1065–umbes 1116","1065–1116":"1065–1116","1087–1149":"1087–1149","1049–Female":"1049–Surnud","1085–1166":"1085–1166","1100–1175":"1100–1175","1105–1187":"1105–1187","1108–Male":"1108–Surnud","1113–1162":"1113–1162","1087–1121":"1087–1121","1040–Male":"1040–Surnud","about 1085":"umbes 1085","1121":"1121","1187":"1187","1065":"1065","Abt 1116":"umbes 1116","1175":"1175","1087":"1087","1162":"1162","1085":"1085","1040":"1040","1105":"1105","1149":"1149","1116":"1116","1049":"1049","1113":"1113","about 1105":"umbes 1105","1100":"1100","1166":"1166","about 1113":"umbes 1113","about 1087":"umbes 1087","about 1100":"umbes 1100","1108":"1108","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Old Abingdon Abbey, Berkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Old Abingdon Abbey, Berkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Edwardstone, Suffolk, England":"Edwardstone, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1065–Abt 1116":"1